Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]] \n|-\n|August 4, 1990\n|[[1990 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]] at [[1990 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodgers Put Giants Over the Coals|author=Bill Plaschke|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=1|date=August 4, 1990}}</ref><br>[[1990 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1990 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis]]<ref>{{cite news|title=NBC Names Fratello, Jones Without Fanfare|author=Jack Craig|newspaper=Boston Globe|page=41|date=August 7, 1990}}</ref>\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]] \n|-\n|August 11, 1990\n|[[1990 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] at [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]]<br>[[1990 Texas Rangers season|Texas]] at [[1990 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Not so super|author=Jack Fogle|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|page=C2|date=August 11, 1990}}</ref>\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|August 12, 1990\n|[[1990 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] at [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]]<ref>{{cite news|title=KGLD Adds Irish To Lineup|author=Dan Caesar|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|page=2D|date=August 10, 1990}}\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Kevin Maas Yankees 1990|id=hp-dBNdXo8M}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 18, 1990\n|[[1990 California Angels season|California]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=MLB Highlights August 18, 1990|id=_BPhshGtCqI}}</ref> at [[1990 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]]<br>[[1990 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]] at [[1990 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]]\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|August 25, 1990\n|[[1990 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1990 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Gott's Streak Ends in Pain for Dodgers Baseball|author=Bill Plaschke|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=1|date=August 25, 1990}}</ref><br>[[1990 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]] at [[1990 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|September 22, 1990\n|[[1990 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis]] at [[1990 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Stephens Catches A Chance|author=Dan O'Neill|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|page=1D|date=September 20, 1990}}</ref><br>[[Yankees \u2013 Red Sox rivalry|Boston at New York Yankees]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS comes up short on baseball identity|author=Prentis Rogers|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|page=D2|date=September 22, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sports on Weekend TV|author=Steven Herbert|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=12|date=September 22, 1990}}</ref>\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|September 29, 1990\n|[[1990 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]] at [[1990 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Clemens' New Target: Saturday|author=Nick Cafardo|authorlink=Nick Cafardo|newspaper=Boston Globe|page=82|date=September 27, 1990}}</ref>\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|}\n\n======Postseason======\nThe 1990 postseason started on a Thursday, while World Series started on a Tuesday due to the brief [[1990 Major League Baseball lockout|lockout]]. Major League Baseball and CBS went with some rather unconventional scheduling during the LCS round, with two consecutive scheduled off-days<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Criticized for Not Introducing All Players|author=Bob Kravitz|newspaper=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|date=October 17, 1990}}</ref> in the [[1990 National League Championship Series|NLCS]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/rec.sport.baseball/CBS$201990/rec.sport.baseball/eSSyrngncwk/DFJAFKJ4g5UJ|title=Bonilla goes for third (and CBS rationalizes)|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=10 October 1990|website=rec.sport.baseball|publisher= |access-date=}}</ref> after Game 2.\n\nAfter NBC lost the Major League Baseball package to CBS, the network aggressively counter-programmed<ref>{{cite news|title=NBC Affiliates Learn Baseball Will Be Replaced by Hodgepodge|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7C3DA46140743&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution |date=May 23, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carter|first=Bill|date=October 4, 1990|title=Rival Networks Face Beloved Game Show On CBS: Baseball|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/04/arts/rival-networks-face-beloved-game-show-on-cbs-baseball.html|newspaper=New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> CBS' postseason baseball coverage with [[television film|made-for-TV movies]] and [[miniseries]] geared towards female viewers.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Series: A CBS Grand Slam|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1991-10-30/entertainment/ca-593_1_world-series|author=Steven Herbert|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 30, 1991}}</ref>\n\nCBS' first year of Major League Baseball postseason coverage in general, proved to be problematic for the network. First and foremost, none of the teams involved in the [[1990 American League Championship Series|ALCS]] ([[1990 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]] and [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]]), [[1990 National League Championship Series|NLCS]] ([[1990 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]] and [[1990 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Storm|first=Jonathan|date=October 10, 1990|title=Baseball Fails To Raise Cbs Batting Average|url=http://articles.philly.com/1990-10-10/news/25894246_1_abc-nbc-s-lifestories-ratings|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|location= |access-date= }}</ref>), and [[1990 World Series|World Series]] (Cincinnati and Oakland) involved teams from [[List of American and Canadian cities by number of major professional sports franchises|baseball's largest media markets]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Nidetz |first=Steve|date=October 15, 1990|title=Baseball Rights No Steal For Cbs|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-15/sports/9003280599_1_abc-and-nbc-major-league-baseball-cbs-john-madden|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref> This more than likely, helped reduce playoff ratings by 9.4% for [[prime time]] games and 3.4% for weekend daytime games. This was below the levels of the playoffs the year before, when they aired on NBC.\n\nWhile the ratings for the 1990 World Series improved to 26.2 compared to [[1989 World Series|1989]], the 1989 Series (which aired on ABC) was interrupted for 10 days by the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake|Loma Prieta earthquake]]. All in all, the 1989 World Series was at the time, the lowest [[World Series television ratings|rated World Series]] ever. More to the point, the ratings for the 1990 World Series on CBS were significantly lower than any World Series between [[1982 World Series|1982]] and [[1988 World Series|1988]].\n\nAlthough the 1990 NLCS lasted six games, that year's ALCS and more importantly, the World Series, lasted only four<ref>{{cite book |last=Cashmore|first=Ellis|date= |title=And There Was Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4MGIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA146&dq=Major+League+Baseball+on+CBS&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qOHqVKzoLsrUoATO1ICIDw&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAzgU#v=onepage&q=Major%20League%20Baseball%20on%20CBS&f=false|location= |publisher= |page=146|isbn= |access-date= }}</ref> out of seven possible games. To put things into proper perspective, by one estimate, CBS lost $5 million for each playoff game not played and US$15.4 million for each World Series game not played. At the end of the day, CBS lost $12 million to $15 million on each of the League Championship Series and World Series games not played, for a total of $36 million to $45 million.\n\n=====1991=====\nAfter sustaining huge losses<ref>{{cite news |last=Shales|first=Tom|date=April 6, 1991|title=CBS NETWORK ELIMINATES 400 JOBS|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1991/04/06/cbs-network-eliminates-400-jobs/600c7663-2fc7-4e2c-a469-597d2b421360/|work=Washington Post|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=4 December 1990|title=CBS Wants Some of Its Money Back After Taking a Bath on Baseball Deal |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-12-04/entertainment/ca-6060_1_baseball-contract|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carter|first=Bill|date=December 26, 1990|title=1990 was a bad year, probably the worst ever, for television|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1990-12-26/features/1990360165_1_television-industry-cbs-three-networks|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref> (CBS claimed to have lost about $55 million<ref>{{cite news |last=Pergament|first=Alan|date=August 2, 1991|title=IT'S NO WONDER THAT CBS SENDS 2ND TEAM TO RICH|url=https://buffalonews.com/1991/08/03/its-no-wonder-that-cbs-sends-2nd-team-to-rich/|work=The Buffalo News|location= |access-date= }}</ref> in after-taxes revenue in 1990,<ref>{{cite news |last=Nidetz|first=Steve|date=5 October 1992|title=Baseball`s Short-term Health Hinges On Tv Contracts|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-10-05/sports/9203310110_1_tv-contracts-major-league-baseball-cable|newspaper=The Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref> which would go up to $170 million at the end of its four-year contract) from 1990's abbreviated postseason (which ended with the [[1990 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati Reds]] shockingly sweeping the defending [[World Series Trophy|World Champion]] [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] in the [[1990 World Series|World Series]]), CBS made several notable adjustments for 1991. Regular season telecasts were reduced to a meager handful. In return, pregame shows during the League Championship Series were entirely eliminated, to minimize the ratings damage.\n\nOn [[Sunday Afternoon Baseball|Sunday]], May 5, CBS broadcast games involving [[1991 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland]] at [[1991 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] (with Jack Buck and Tim McCarver on the call) and [[1991 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]] at the [[1991 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] (with Dick Stockton and Jim Kaat on the call). And then on Sunday, July 14, Dick Stockton and Jim Kaat called a game in [[Angel Stadium|Anaheim]] between the [[1991 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] and [[1991 California Angels season|California Angels]].\n\nFor CBS' coverage of the [[1991 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1991 All-Star Game]] from [[Rogers Centre|Toronto]], CBS started their broadcast at the top of the hour with the customary pregame coverage. And then, because [[President of the United States|American President]] [[George Herbert Walker Bush|George H.W. Bush]] and [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Brian Mulroney]] were throwing out the first ball, there was a slight delay from the 8:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] start. The game eventually started about 15\u201320 minutes late. Presumably this, along with CBS' low ratings for baseball, and the costs of doing pregame coverage, led to them starting the prime time broadcasts at 8:30 for the final two years of the contract, with little or no pregame content.\n\nThe 1991 season was perhaps most noteworthy for CBS having the opportunity to cover the now legendary [[1991 World Series|World Series]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Hansen|first=Jeff|date=October 21, 1991|title=CBS blinded by baseball's shining moment|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1991/10/21/CBS-blinded-by-baseballs-shining-moment/8427688017600/|newspaper=UPI|location= |access-date= }}</ref> between the [[1991 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]] and [[1991 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]]. The tightly contested, seven-game affair<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=28 October 1991|title=Baseball Daily Report|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-10-28/sports/sp-516_1_extra-games|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> between Minnesota and Atlanta earned CBS the highest ratings for a World Series<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldenrankings.com/ultimategame1991.htm|title=The Ultimate Game|last= |first= |date= |website=Golden Baseball Magazine |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> since the [[1986 World Series]] between the [[1986 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] and [[1986 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] on NBC.\n\nEarlier in the postseason, CBS' coverage of the [[1991 American League Championship Series|ALCS]] meant that they could not carry the live testimony of [[Clarence Thomas]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenberg|first=Alan|date=October 16, 1991|title=MANY WEEKEND WINNERS, BUT CBS NOT AMONG THEM|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1991-10-16-0000210780-story.html|work=Hartford Courant|location= |access-date= }}</ref>, whose confirmation to the [[United States Supreme Court]] was put into question because of charges of [[sexual harassment]] from former staffer [[Anita Hill]]. Meanwhile, [[ABC News|ABC]], [[NBC News|NBC]], [[CNN]] and [[PBS]] all carried the testimony.\n\nAs previously mentioned, as CBS' baseball coverage<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS still striking out Baseball playoffs won't end diamond nightmare|author=Jim Baker|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|page=B18|date=October 6, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV Sports; McCarver and Buck Need Time|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/18/sports/tv-sports-mccarver-and-buck-need-time.html?pagewanted=print|author=Richard Sandomir|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 18, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Hopes Baseball Playoffs Prove Bigger Hit Than Season|author=Steven Herbert|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=2|date=October 8, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Not much `Hawk' in Kaat's coverage|author=Steve Nidetz|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=9|date=October 4, 1991}}</ref> progressed, the network dropped its 8:00&nbsp;p.m. pregame coverage<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS scraps pregame baseball playoff shows|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=October 3, 1991}}</ref> (in favor of airing [[sitcom]]s such as ''[[Evening Shade]]''), before finally starting their coverage at 8:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]. The first pitch would generally arrive at approximately 8:45&nbsp;p.m. Perhaps as a result, [[Joe Carter]]'s [[1993 World Series|World Series]] clinching [[home run]] off [[Mitch Williams (baseball)|Mitch Williams]] in 1993, occurred at 12&nbsp;a.m. on the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]].\n\n======Regular season======\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\"\n|'''Date'''\n|'''Teams'''\n|'''Announcers'''\n|-\n|April 20,<ref>{{cite news|title=WNYers are Saturated with Baseball on Cable|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB195E13A31A686&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|author=Alan Pergament|newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=April 7, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Camera work gives TVKO split decision|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7D0AE16729A69&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 7, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref> 1991\n|[[1991 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1991 Montreal Expos season|Montreal]]<ref>{{cite news|title=1994 game plan for NBC Sports: Regain baseball, keep Bob Costas|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WT&