 Jays season|Toronto]] at [[1991 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]]<br>[[1991 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh]] at [[1991 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|August 24, 1991\n|[[1991 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]] at [[1991 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]<br>[[1991 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] at [[1991 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|September 14, 1991\n|[[1991 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] at [[1991 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Stature of SportSouth grows; no-hitter helps|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7D0E948FF9D61&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Credit GM Schuerholz for Braves' Turnaround|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/88997095.html?dids=88997095:88997095&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+02%2C+1991&author=Larry+Guest+of+The+Sentinel+Staff&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=CREDIT+GM+SCHUERHOLZ+FOR+BRAVES'+TURNAROUND&pqatl=google|author=Larry Guest|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=September 2, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref><br>[[1991 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] at [[1991 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|September 21,<ref>{{cite news|title=A Fear: Foes In NFL Derby May 'Cash In'|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB04D57EDAE695D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|author=Bernie Miklasz|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=September 21, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref> 1991\n|[[1991 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] at [[1991 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]]\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|September 28,<ref>{{cite news|title=Braves Have Winner with Sutton in Broadcast Booth|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RO&p_theme=ro&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAEA23C04F4DB8D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[The Roanoke Times]]|date=September 28, 2012|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref> 1991\n|[[1991 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco]] at [[1991 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]]<br>[[1991 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]] at [[1991 Houston Astros season|Houston]]\n|[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|October 5, 1991\n|[[1991 Houston Astros season|Houston]] at [[1991 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1991 Atlanta Braves-(Game 161) win the Division over the LA Dodgers-10/05/1991|id=Os8vIo369rQ}}</ref><br>[[1991 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]] at [[1991 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco]]\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Jack Buck]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|}\n\n====Sean McDonough replaces Jack Buck====\nAfter two years of calling baseball telecasts for CBS,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cbs Forges Its Own Era Of Deadball|url=http://articles.courant.com/1992-10-23/sports/0000110842_1_sean-mcdonough-jack-buck-televising-baseball|author=Jerry Trecker|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=October 23, 1992}}</ref> Jack Buck was dismissed in December 1991. According to the [[KMOX (AM)|radio]] veteran Buck, he had a hard time adjusting to the demands of a more constricting television production.<ref>{{cite news|title=Announcing switch works well for CBS|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/announcing-switch-works-well-for-cbs/article_ecbd5105-49a7-5ed0-b223-d654f5f0f687.html|author=Barry Lewis|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|date=May 1, 1992}}</ref> CBS felt that Buck should have done more to make himself appear to be a set-up man for lead analyst Tim McCarver.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball TV Sports; Will Pennant Races Be Good for Business?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/09/sports/baseball-tv-sports-will-pennant-races-be-good-for-business.html?pagewanted=print|author=Richard Sandomir|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 9, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=April 10, 1992|title=TV SPORTS; It's Easy to 'Pig Out' at This Buffet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/10/sports/tv-sports-it-s-easy-to-pig-out-at-this-buffet.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> Jack Buck's son [[Joe Buck|Joe]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Halberstam|first=David J.|date=September 14, 2018|title=Halby\u2019s Morsels: When a brash Tim McCarver dissed Jack Buck on-air; Aikman, Collinsworth, Joe Buck +|url=http://www.sportsbroadcastjournal.com/halbys-morsels-when-a-brash-tim-mccarver-dissed-jack-buck-on-air-aikman-collinsworth-joe-buck/|work=Sports Business Journal|location= |access-date= }}</ref> tried to rationalize his father's on-air problems by saying \"My dad was brought up in the [[Old-time radio|golden age of radio]], I think he had his hands tied somewhat, being accustomed to the freedom of radio.<ref name=\"Rudy Martzke 3C\">{{cite news|title=Sunday dinner puts Gumbel on sideline|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=October 5, 1993}}</ref> I'm more used to acquiescing to what the producer wants to do, what the director wants to do.\"\n\nBuck himself sized up CBS' handling of the announcers by saying \"CBS never got that baseball play-by-play draws word-pictures. All they knew was that football stars analysts. So they said, 'Let [analyst Tim] McCarver run the show.' In television, all they want you to do is shut up. I'm not very good at shutting up.\" Buck though, would add that although he knew Tim McCarver well, they never developed a good relationship with each other on the air<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=April 10, 1992|title=TV SPORTS; It's Easy to 'Pig Out' at This Buffet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/10/sports/tv-sports-it-s-easy-to-pig-out-at-this-buffet.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> despite high hopes to the contrary. [[Phil Mushnick]] added insult to injury to Buck by accusing him of \"trying to predict plays<ref>{{cite news |last=Frager|first=Ray|date=October 25, 1991|title=Buck, early with his calls, trapped off base Top dog at CBS not having his day|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1991-10-25-1991298076-story.html|work=The Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref>, as if to prove he was still on top.\"\n\n{{quote|My biggest problem was understanding my role. They wanted him to dominate the broadcast and have me be the mechanic and stay out of the way. I didn't want to broadcast that way. I guess I should have accepted it, but relying on my experience on ''GrandStand'' (NBC's NFL pregame show that Buck hosted in [[1975 NFL season|1975]]) when I had not challenged anyone, I couldn't let others make all the decisions that put me in a position where I couldn't perform at all.|Jack Buck in his autobiography ''That's a Winner''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Buck|first=Jack|date= |title=Jack Buck: \u00d2That's a Winner!\u00d3 \u2013 The 1990s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D3roBAAAQBAJ&dq=You+Can%27t+Make+This+Up%3A+Miracles%2C+Memories%2C+and+the+Perfect+Marriage+of+Sports+and+Television&q=CBS#v=snippet&q=CBS&f=false|location= |publisher=Sports Publishing|page= |isbn= |access-date= }}</ref>}}\n\nBuck also got into deep trouble with CBS executives (namely [[executive producer]] Ted Shaker) over questionable comments made towards singer [[Bobby Vinton]] in 1990. While on-air prior to Game 4 of [[1990 National League Championship Series|that year's NLCS]] in [[Three Rivers Stadium|Pittsburgh]], Buck criticized Vinton's off-key rendition of \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", making a comment towards Vinton that sounded like a prejudicial remark centered on his [[Polish culture|Polish]] heritage.<ref>{{YouTube|title=vinton nat'l anthem 1990 nlcs game 4.mpg|id=BkNNy8BxtDA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=October 11, 1990|title=Vinton, Buck Apologize for Wayward Words : Baseball: Singer flubbed national anthem and sportscaster's remarks angered Polish community.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-11/sports/sp-3218_1_national-anthem|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 11, 1990|title=Polish group takes broadcaster Buck to task|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4021189.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021031738/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4021189.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 21, 2012|work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref> Joe Buck believed that the situation was ironic because his father was \"trying to help the guy.\" Buck began receiving death threats from [[1990 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pirate]] fans and discovered a footprint on his pillow once he returned to his hotel room.\n\n=====1992=====\nBuck's replacement was [[Boston Red Sox]] announcer [[Sean McDonough]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Too much of good thing a problem for NBC|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=January 9, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Trecker|first=Jerry|date=October 23, 1992|title=CBS FORGES ITS OWN ERA OF DEADBALL|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1992-10-23-0000110842-story.html|work=Hartford Courant|location= |access-date= }}</ref> Ted Shaker called McDonough about his interests for the top announcing job, and after McDonough hung up the telephone, he claimed that he did not want to \"act like a 10-year-old\" but he \"jumped so high that he put a hole in his ceiling.\" McDonough, who was 30 years old at the time, became the youngest full-time network announcer to call a World Series when he called that year's Fall Classic alongside McCarver.\n\nFor CBS' coverage of the [[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992 All-Star Game]],<ref>{{cite news|title=McDonough Takes Advice to the Bank|author=Larry Stewart|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=3|date=July 10, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Show Recalls Baseball in B.G. (Before Greed) Era|author=Alan Pergament|newspaper=The Buffalo News|date=July 11, 1992}}</ref> they introduced Basecam,<ref>{{cite news|title=NBC reconsiders schedule with Dream Team ratings|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=July 7, 1992}}</ref> a lipstick-size camera, inside first base.\n\nOver the course of Game 2 of the [[1992 American League Championship Series|1992 ALCS]], Jim Kaat was stricken with a bad case of laryngitis.<ref>{{cite news|title=No Quarrel by La Russa with Ruling on Wild Pitch|author=Bob Kravitz|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|date=October 9, 1992}}</ref> As a result, [[Johnny Bench]] had to come over from the [[Major League Baseball on CBS Radio|CBS Radio]] booth and finish the game with Dick Stockton as a \"relief analyst.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Football analysts campaign for replay's return|author=Steve Nidetz|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=13|date=October 12, 1992}}</ref> There was talk that if Kaat's laryngitis did not get better, [[Don Drysdale]] was going to replace Kaat on television for Game 3, while Bench would continue to work on CBS Radio.\n\nTim McCarver ran afoul of [[1992 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]] outfielder [[Deion Sanders]] during the 1992 postseason,<ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball, Football, Hockey in Rare Three-Way Collision|author=Dusty Saunders|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|date=October 5, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV Sports; McCarver Can't Keep a Knuckleballer Straight|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/13/sports/tv-sports-mccarver-can-t-keep-a-knuckleballer-straight.html?pagewanted=print|author=Richard Sandomir|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 13, 1992}}</ref> when he made comments on-air criticizing Sanders for his two-sport athletic career; Sanders was playing for both the Braves and the NFL's [[1992 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] at the time and participated in both the baseball postseason and the early NFL regular season for the first time in 1992 (Sanders was unable to do this in [[1991 Atlanta Braves season|1991]], as his NFL contract with the [[1991 Atlanta Falcons season|Falcons]] would not allow him to). Sanders retaliated following Game 7 of the [[1992 National League Championship Series|NLCS]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadspin.com/5502736/pittsburgh-pirates-october-14-1992|title=Pittsburgh Pirates: October 14, 1992|last1=Leitch|first1=Will|last2= |first2= |date=March 26, 2010|website=Deadspin|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> by dumping a bucket of ice water on McCarver (who was wired for sound and feared electrocution).\n\nMcCarver was not immune to criticism from outside sources, either, as [[Norman Chad]] wrote a critique of him in ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' during the postseason. Chad said that McCarver was someone who \"when you ask him the time, will tell you how a watch works\", a reference to McCarver's perceived tendency to overanalyze<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1811185-the-best-major-league-baseball-announcers-of-all-time#slide1|title=The Best Major League Baseball Announcers of All Time|last=Levy|first=Dan|date=October 16, 2013|website=Bleacher Report|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> things. Chad went further by saying \"What's the difference between Tim McCarver and [[appendicitis]]? Appendicitis is covered by most health plans.\"\n\nMcCarver was also known to make gaffes from time to time. One of his more amusing miscues came during the [[1992 National League Championship Series]] when he repeatedly referred to [[1992 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]] pitcher [[Tim Wakefield]] as \"Bill Wakefield.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Steve|first=Nidetz|date=October 19, 1992|title=Mcdonough Does It Right The 1st Time|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-10-19/sports/9204040766_1_red-sox-telecasts-mcdonough-doesn-t-tim-mccarver|work=Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref> He finally explained that Bill Wakefield was one of his old minor-league teammates, and he laughed at himself because \"I forgot my own name!\" The year prior, during Game 6 of the [[1991 World Series|World Series]], McCarver's broadcast colleague, Jack Buck talked about [[1991 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]] third baseman [[Terry Pendleton]], who hit .367 in the series. Buck said, \"TP. That's what his teammates call him.\" A few seconds later, McCarver rather oddly added, \"[[Tipi|TP]]. An appropriate name for someone who plays on the Braves.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The \u201991 Series: McCarver, Kirby and Herbie|url=http://tvfury.wordpress.com/2011/10/28/the-91-series-mccarver-kirby-and-herbie/|website=TVFury|date=October 28, 2011|accessdate=February 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1992 postseason, CBS missed covering one of the [[1992 United States presidential election|three debates]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Wanted Braves in Series But Not the Blue Jays as Much|author=Jerry Greene|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|page=D2|date=October 16, 1992}}</ref> among U.S. presidential candidates [[George Herbert Walker Bush|George H.W. Bush]], [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Ross Perot|H. Ross Perot]]. CBS had planned to join other broadcast and cable networks in the telecast; however, Game 4 of the [[1992 American League Championship Series|ALCS]] between the [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]] and [[1992 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] did not end until 8:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Time, about the time the debate ended. The Blue Jays won the game 7-6 in 11 innings. The other networks reported very good ratings for the debate, part of one of the more compelling election campaigns in recent times.\n\n======Regular season======\n:''Note: All times eastern''\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\"\n|'''Date'''\n|'''Teams'''\n|'''Announcers'''\n|-\n|April 18, 1992<ref>{{cite news|title=Buck says Jays stop here \u2013 on top|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/454309011.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+05%2C+1992&author=Ken+McKee+TORONTO+STAR&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=Buck+says+Jays+stop+here+-+on+top&pqatl=google|author=Ken McKee|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=April 5, 2012|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n|[[Cardinals\u2013Cubs rivalry|Chicago Cubs at St. Louis]]<br>[[1992 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit]] at [[1992 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]]\n|[[Sean McDonough]]<ref name=\"Sandomir, Richard\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=New Voice, Familiar Name at CBS Nepotism Charges Haven't Slowed McDonough's Climb to the Top|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB346575F810502&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[Miami Herald]]|date=April 17, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=CBS announcer has uneasy start|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24397667.html?dids=24397667:24397667&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+17%2C+1992&author=Steve+Nidetz.&pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=CBS+announcer+has+uneasy+start&pqatl=google|author=Steve Nidetz|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 17, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> and [[Tim McCarver]]<ref>{{cite news|title=McCarver, CBS team up again|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7D42DF6CDC523&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 18, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref><br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|April 25, 1992\n|[[1992 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] at [[1992 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Team Kiper Ready to Praise or Pan His 28 NFL Peers|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PD&s_site=twincities&p_multi=SP&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB5DBBFF63AA0B2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=April 24, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<ref>{{cite news|title=ESPN draft coverage mostly tight, on target|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/56200259.html?dids=56200259:56200259&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+27%2C+1992&author=Rudy+Martzke&pub=USA+TODAY+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=ESPN+draft+coverage+mostly+tight%2C+on+target&pqatl=google|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|date=April 27, 1992 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|May 2, 1992\n|[[Braves\u2013Mets rivalry|New York Mets at Atlanta]]<br>[[1992 Texas Rangers season|Texas]] at [[1992 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Dick Stockton]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Training Methods To Benefit Arazi?|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=l4dGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OukMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1177,618003&dq=sean+mcdonough&hl=en|author=Ken Schott|newspaper=[[The Daily Gazette]]|date=May 2, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Sean McDonough]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Greenie in swing|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/68779355.html?dids=68779355:68779355&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+29%2C+1992&author=JOE+GIULIOTTI&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Greenie+in+swing&pqatl=google|author=Joe Giuliotti|newspaper=Boston Herald|date=April 29, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> and [[Tim McCarver]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/rec.sport.baseball/CBS$201992/rec.sport.baseball/7TRjC-futI8/RrwhQeVMc5YJ|title=Keith Mitchell, Invisible Man|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=2 May 1992|website=rec.sport.baseball|publisher= |access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 13, 1992\n|[[1992 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]] at [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] (10&nbsp;p.m.)<br>[[1992 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1992 MLB Highlights May 30 to June 14|id=svZ7syt0b7M}}</ref> at [[1992 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]]<ref>{{cite news|title=On the Air Bulls' blowout blows CBS' ratings|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/68782989.html?dids=68782989:68782989&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+05%2C+1992&author=JIM+BAKER&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=ON+THE+AIR+Bulls'+blowout+blows+CBS'+ratings&pqatl=google|author=Jim Baker|newspaper=Boston Herald|date=June 5, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> (1 p.m.)\n|[[Sean McDonough]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Complex Christensen Simply Quits|author=Larry Stewart|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=3|date=June 12, 1992}}</ref> and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|June 20, 1992\n|[[1992 San Diego Padres season|San Diego]] at [[1992 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco]] (3&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|June 27, 1992\n|[[1992 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1992 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis]]<br>[[1992 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=CBS Commercial Block from Jun.24/92 Pt.2|id=uw7etM6QLfQ}}</ref> at [[1992 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]]\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|July 4, 1992\n|[[1992 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Say What? & Major League Baseball promos, 1992|id=l0STn_tfuI8}}</ref> at [[1992 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]]<br>[[1992 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]] at [[1992 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oocities.org/tbtho/foxbox.htm|title=I Invented the Fox Box|last=Thomas |first=Thomas Buckingham|date=August 16, 2000|website=ocities.org|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|July 11, 1992\n|[[1992 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis]] at [[1992 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles]]\n|[[Sean McDonough]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS' McDonough goes on defense after remarks|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/56211809.html?dids=56211809:56211809&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+14%2C+1992&author=Rudy+Martzke&pub=USA+TODAY+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=CBS'+McDonough+goes+on+defense+after+remarks&pqatl=google|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|date=July 14, 1992 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|July 14, 1992\n|[[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1992 MLB Highlights July 12 to July 29|id=oLFzDhbLhOw}}</ref> ([[Jack Murphy Stadium]], [[San Diego]]; 8&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|July 18, 1992\n|[[1992 Texas Rangers season|Texas]] at [[1992 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|July 25, 1992\n|[[1992 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota]] at [[1992 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]]<br>[[1992 Texas Rangers season|Texas]] at [[1992 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]]\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|August 1, 1992\n|[[1992 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] at [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)<br>[[1992 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] at [[1992 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|August 8, 1992<ref>{{cite news|title=Musburger opts for style over substance Series: Radio / TV|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/54250906.html?dids=54250906:54250906&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+22%252C+1992&author=JOHN+HARRIS&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=Musburger+opts+for+style+over+substance+Series%253A+RADIO+%252F+TV&pqatl=google|author=John Harris|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=June 22, 1992|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> \n|[[1992 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] at [[1992 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]]<br>[[1992 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1992 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|August 29, 1992\n|[[1992 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]] at [[1992 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]<br>[[1992 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee]] at [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] (1&nbsp;p.m.)\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|September 19, 1992\n|[[1992 Texas Rangers season|Texas]] at [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] (3&nbsp;p.m.)<br>[[1992 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]] at [[1992 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee]]\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|September 26, 1992\n|[[1992 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] at [[1992 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1992 MLB Highlights Sept. 10 to Sept. 26|id=uAZDAzMONos}}</ref><br>[[1992 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1992 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]]\n|[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MLB Library |url=http://geocities.com/afc1994/baseball.html |website=Sports Game Library|accessdate=October 30, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021133353/http://geocities.com/afc1994/baseball.html |archivedate=October 21, 2009 }}</ref><br>[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|October 3, 1992\n|[[1992 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit]] at [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] (3&nbsp;p.m.)<br>[[1992 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee]] at [[1992 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1992 MLB Highlights Sept. 27 to Oct. 3|id=vdGmhduiuSI}}</ref>\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Timeless Toronto Sports Moment \u2013 Blue Jays Win 92 Division Title|id=0aY71QMNl14}}</ref><br>[[Dick Stockton]] and [[Jim Kaat]] \n|}\n\n=====1993=====\nLesley Visser missed the first half of the [[1993 in baseball|1993 season]] due to injuries earlier suffered in a bizarre jogging accident in New York City's [[Central Park]]. Visser broke her hip and skidded face-first across the pavement, requiring reconstructive plastic surgery on her face and more than a decade later required an artificial hip replacement. She missed the [[1993 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|Major League Baseball All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaston gets rebuke from CBS|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|page=E2|date=July 14, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Diamond Showcase CBS' Tim McCarver is a Natural to Analyze All-Star Game|author=John Scheibe|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=4|date=July 11, 1993}}</ref> Jim Kaat would replace her while she recuperated. Jim Gray also served as a reporter for the All-Star Game<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/rec.sport.baseball/CBS$201993/rec.sport.baseball/HyZ-4hRSBls/Y2FDtPNWUkEJ|title=All Star Game comments...|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=13 July 1993|website=rec.sport.baseball|publisher= |access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Frager|first=Ray|date=11 July 1993|title=Welcome to the Show: CBS plans major-league coverage of game|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1993-07-11/sports/1993192137_1_cbs-dekas-all-star-game|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref> and [[1993 World Series|World Series]].\n\nAs previously mentioned, for 1993, CBS made a broadcast booth change by removing Dick Stockton from his role as secondary play-by-play announcer after three seasons, and replacing him with Greg Gumbel. Also as previously mentioned, also during the 1993 season, Andrea Joyce replaced Gumbel<ref name=\"Rudy Martzke 3C\"/> as studio host. Joyce would be joined at the anchor desk by Pat O'Brien. At the [[1993 World Series]], she became the first woman to co-host the network television coverage for a World Series. Sean McDonough<ref>{{cite news |last=Dearth|first=Sonny|date=October 15, 1993|title=CBS GETS GOOD MARKS FOR BASEBALL COVERAGE, EXCEPT FOR 2 THINGS|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/dp-xpm-19931015-1993-10-15-9310150279-story.html|work=Daily Press|location= |access-date= }}</ref> filled in for O'Brien, who was suffering from [[laryngitis]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Fleischman|first=Bill|date=October 14, 1993|title=The Right Touch Cbs's Pictures Tell Celebration Story|url=http://articles.philly.com/1993-10-14/sports/25939149_1_dave-hollins-darren-daulton-mitch-williams|newspaper=Philadelphia Daily News|location= |access-date= }}</ref> as the pregame host for Game 6 of the [[1993 National League Championship Series]]. Game 6<ref>{{cite news |last=Dearth|first=Sonny|date=October 15, 1993|title=CBS GETS GOOD MARKS FOR BASEBALL COVERAGE, EXCEPT FOR 2 THINGS|url=https://www.dailypress.com/news/dp-xpm-19931015-1993-10-15-9310150279-story.html|work=Daily Press|location= |access-date= }}</ref> of the NLCS by the way, didn't have its first pitch until nearly 8:50&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] so that CBS could run ''[[60 Minutes]]'' in its entirety.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dearth |first=Sonny|date=October 15, 1993|title=CBS GETS GOOD MARKS FOR BASEBALL COVERAGE, EXCEPT FOR 2 THINGS|url=https://www.dailypress.com/news/dp-xpm-19931015-1993-10-15-9310150279-story.html|work=Daily Press|location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nDuring CBS' coverage of the World Series,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=October 15, 1993|title=WORLD SERIES: TV SPORTS; CBS Is Getting Out Just as It Gets It Right|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/15/sports/world-series-tv-sports-cbs-is-getting-out-just-as-it-gets-it-right.html|newspaper=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> umpires were upset with the [[Skycam|overhead]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/rec.sport.baseball/CBS$201993/rec.sport.baseball/lgF3djqENfM/9ciia_zlqcEJ|title=Umps ask CBS not to use Skydome roof camera|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=15 October 1993|website=rec.sport.baseball|publisher= |access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Nidetz|first=Steve|date=18 October 1993|title=Cbs Balks At Pitch To Ban Overhead Camera|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-10-18/sports/9310180022_1_major-league-baseball-cbs-executive-producer-umpires|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref> replays being televised by CBS. [[Dave Phillips (umpire)|Dave Phillips]], the crew chief, said just prior to Game 2 that the umpires want \"CBS to be fair with their approach.\" [[Rick Gentile]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Frager|first=Ray|date=October 15, 1993|title=CBS gets last at-laugh with Phillies|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1993-10-15/sports/1993288118_1_phillies-cbs-rim-shot|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref> senior vice president for production for CBS Sports, said that [[Richie Phillips]], the lawyer for the Major League Umpires Association, tried to call the broadcast booth during Saturday's game, but the call was not put through. Richie Phillips apparently was upset when Dave Phillips called the [[1993 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]' [[Ricky Jordan]] out on strikes in the fourth inning, and a replay showed the pitch to be about 6&nbsp;inches outside. [[National League]] President [[Bill White (first baseman)|Bill White]], while using a CBS headset in the broadcast booth during Game 1, was overheard telling Gentile and the producer Bob Dekas, \"You guys keep using that camera the way you want. Don't let Phillips intimidate you.\"\n\n======Regular season======\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\"\n|'''Date'''\n|'''Teams'''\n|'''Announcers'''\n|-\n|April 17, 1993<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Baseball Enjoy It|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=VP&p_theme=vp&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFF63F57670422&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|author=Larry Bonko|newspaper=[[The Virginian-Pilot]]|date=April 5, 1993|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref>\n|[[1993 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] at [[1993 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]]<br>[[1993 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] at [[1993 Boston Red Sox season|Boston]]\n|[[Greg Gumbel]] and [[Jim Kaat]]<br>[[Sean McDonough]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports on the Air Caray to ESPN, CBS: `Be a man'|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/68101319.html?dids=68101319:68101319&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+04%2C+1993&author=Jim+Baker&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Sports+on+the+Air+Caray+to+ESPN%2C+CBS%3A+%60Be+a+man'&pqatl=google|author=Jim Baker|newspaper=Boston Herald|date=April 4, 1993|accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> and [[Tim McCarver]]\n|-\n|April 24, 1993\n|[[1993 Florida Marlins season|Florida]] at [[1993 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rockies-Cubs Blackout is on But Dial WGN, Just in Case|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RM&p_theme=rm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB4DC689A656C44&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|author=Dusty Sanders|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|date=April 26, 1993|accessdate=March 15, 2012}}</ref><br>[[1993 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati]] at [[1993 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]]\n|[[Sean McDonough]] and [[Tim McCarver]]<br>[[Greg Gumbel]] and [[Jim Kaat]]\n|-\n|May 1, 1993\n|[[1993 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Loui